  "Idea": "This paper introduces a novel neuro-symbolic meta-learning framework, LambdaNPI, designed to investigate and enhance the ability of language models to generalize monotonicity-based negative polarity item (NPI) licensing to syntactically and semantically unseen environments—without explicit exposure to NPI occurrences during initial training. While prior work has established that models struggle with systematic generalization under structural variation (as shown in Paper 3), and recent benchmarks like MonotNPI aim to diagnose such failures, no existing approach attempts to *train* models to acquire abstract semantic principles governing monotonicity. LambdaNPI bridges this gap by integrating symbolic logic induction into neural training through differentiable logical form manipulation. Specifically, we generate a synthetic pre-training corpus grounded in typed lambda calculus, where each sentence is paired with its denotational semantics and monotonicity signature (upward/downward/none). During an intermediate meta-pretraining phase, models are exposed to contrastive logical templates that systematically vary syntactic realization while preserving semantic entailment and monotonicity frame. For example, 'No student read any book' and 'It is not the case that any student read a book' share the same downward-entailing context but differ in syntactic structure and scope configuration. Using a differentiable parser and semantic executor, we backpropagate through logical consistency errors—rewarding models not just for surface acceptability, but for maintaining stable interpretations across transformations. We further introduce 'predicate invention probes,' inspired by NOPI (Paper 1), where models must infer latent licensing conditions in zero-shot NPI environments by analogy to learned logical schemata. Evaluation occurs on a held-out test set featuring entirely novel syntactic constructions (e.g., complex quantifier scoping, cross-clausal NPIs, topicalized negation) absent from both standard pretraining and meta-pretraining corpora. Critically, all lexical items and n-grams appear in training, isolating generalization to structural composition. The framework enables us to answer not only whether models *can* generalize, but whether they *can be taught* to do so via implicit rule scaffolding. If successful, LambdaNPI demonstrates that systematicity in language models is not purely emergent but can be cultivated through semantically grounded meta-learning—offering a pathway toward more cognitively plausible AI systems. Even partial success would identify which components of monotonicity reasoning are learnable versus hard-coded, informing future architecture design.",
